</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Short-Term T-Bill Rates Rise to 2-Year High: The Treasury Department sold 
$11.4 billion of new three-month bills at an average discount rate of 3.85%, up 
from 3.76% last week. Another $11.4 billion of new six-month bills was sold at 
an average discount rate of 4.25%, up from 4.21%.The three-month bill rate was 
the highest since they sold for 3.95% on April 6, 1992. The six-month bill rate 
was the highest since they averaged 4.27% on April 27, 1992. The new discount 
rates understate the actual return to investors: 3.94% for three-month bills, 
with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,902.70, and 4.40% for a six-month bill 
selling for $9,785.10. The discount rate reflects the price discount received 
when government securities are purchased at less than face value. T-Bill 
Auction 
</P>
<P>
 3-month: 3.85% 
</P>
<P>
 6-month: 4.25% 
</P>
