<HEADLINE>
<P>
FORECLOSURES INCREASE AT SLOWER RATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEBORA VRANA, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The number of real estate foreclosures in Orange County increased during the 
first three months of this year but at a slower rate than in previous quarters, 
indicating that the beleaguered market may be stabilizing. 
</P>
<P>
 Lenders took back 1,486 Orange County homes and commercial properties during 
the first three months of 1994, up 2.8% from 1,446 properties for the previous 
quarter, according to figures released Monday by TRW Redi Property Data, a real 
estate data firm in Riverside. 
</P>
<P>
 While the number of foreclosures across Southern California is still on the 
rise, the rate of increase has leveled off from last year's double-digit 
increases. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a trend," said Nima Nattagh, an analyst with TRW. "I think foreclosures 
will continue to stabilize for the rest of 1994. 
</P>
<P>
 "There is a gradual real estate recovery on the way, in particular in Orange 
County."  
</P>
<P>
 During the first quarter, lenders took back 14,430 properties in the six 
Southern California counties, an increase of 4.8% from the previous quarter and 
of 32% from the first quarter of 1993. 
</P>
<P>
 The regional numbers do not yet indicate foreclosures that might result from 
January's Northridge earthquake. Typically, about four months elapse from the 
time that an owner defaults on a mortgage until the lender forecloses on the 
property. 
</P>
<P>
 TRW Redi estimates that about 85% of the latest quarter's foreclosures were on 
single-family homes. 
</P>
<P>
 Riverside County showed the region's largest increase in foreclosures: 14.3%. 
More Foreclosures, But Rate Slows 
</P>
<P>
 Property repossessions are still rising in Southern California, but the rate 
of increase has stabilized. During the first quarter of this year, lenders 
foreclosed on 14,430 properties in the Southern California six-county region, 
an increase of 4.8% from the previous quarter, but well below the double-digit 
quarterly increases of early 1993. 06,18,09,09,09,09,09 *4*1993 1994 First 
Second Third Fourth First County quarter quarter quarter quarter quarter Los 
Angeles 5,074 5,732 6,575 6,482 6,606 Orange 1,198 1,257 1,474 1,446 1,486 
Riverside 1,552 1,735 2,024 2,006 2,292 San Bernardino 1,612 1,769 2,078 2,016 
2,170 San Diego 1,093 1,148 1,348 1,371 1,437 Ventura 393 375 417 450 439 
Six-county total 10,922 12,016 13,916 13,771 14,430  
</P>
<P>
 Source: TRW REDI Property Data 
</P>
