<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: JOHANNESBURG; FREE POLLS, AT LAST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 South Africans of all races go to the polls today, Wednesday and Thursday in 
the first election in which the black majority can vote after nearly 350 years 
of white-minority rule. 
</P>
<P>
 The African National Congress is expected to win a majority among the more 
than 25 contesting parties.Its leader, Nelson Mandela, jailed for more than a 
quarter of a century by the white regime, would thus become president of South 
Africa's first post-apartheid government. 
</P>
<P>
 Security will be tight to guard against violence, which scarred election 
campaigning in Natal and has broken out in Johannesburg in the last few days. A 
heavy turnout is expected at the 9,000 polling booths throughout the country. 
The electorate will vote for the parties of their choice, not individuals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
