<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEEKEND BOX OFFICE; 'GIRLS' BADDER THAN THE COMPETITION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID J. FOX 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In peak moviegoing periods, a $5-million gross for the weekend might be good 
enough for seventh or eighth place in the Top 10. But during a slow period, as 
now, $5 million is all it takes to be No. 1.And so "Bad Girls," a tale of four 
prostitutes in the Old West, made it to the top in its opening weekend with a 
$5-million gross. 
</P>
<P>
 Besides "Bad Girls," the weekend's other new movies--"The Inkwell" from 
Disney's Touchstone's division, "Brainscan" from Triumph and "Chasers" from 
Warner Bros.--failed to make much of a commercial impression. "Chasers," on 782 
screens, only grossed $733,859.  
</P>
<P>
 * The Mexican-made romantic tale "Like Water for Chocolate" is poised to 
surpass the all-time box-office record for a foreign-language movie playing in 
the United States in the first week of May. The record was held by the 1969 
Swedish-made soft-porn movie "I Am Curious Yellow," which had a gross of $20.2 
