<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COUNTYWIDE; SWIMMERS WARNED ABOUT STORM DRAINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Beach-goers should avoid the water near storm drains for up to 72 hours after 
rainfall because of fecal bacteria and other waste products being washed into 
the ocean, the Orange County Health Agency warned on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 Among materials being flushed into the ocean are animal wastes, fertilizers, 
road oils and litter, said Robert E. Merryman, director of the health agency. 
</P>
<P>
 After rains, the level of potentially unhealthful bacteria in ocean waters can 
be particularly high. Swimmers and beach-goers should take special care to 
avoid storm drains, rivers and creeks that feed into the ocean, Merryman said. 
</P>
<P>
 With separate pipe systems, sewage drains are not normally a problem after 
rains, he said.FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</TEXT>
