<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAUGH LINES: OBJECTIONS? UH, THIS ANGRY MOB HAS A FEW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICH TOSCHES, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The people, who have just plain had it up to here, have herded all the lawyers 
together and begin now to attack them with really sharp toothpicks, poking them 
mercilessly on their sweaty heads and causing much discomfort. 
</P>
<P>
 The mob puts the toothpicks away and commences yanking with gusto on the 
lawyers' nose hairs, making them yelp. Then the crowd produces biting fire ants 
and. . . . Oops. Sorry. Just a recurring little dream. 
</P>
<P>
 It might have something to do with divorce lawyers -- and who could dismiss 
their contributions to society? -- particularly the one who demanded 13 years 
ago that I give my refrigerator to the woman who left me for a proctologist. 
(Trust me: You can't make something like that up.) 
</P>
<P>
 Anyway, maybe one day my dream might be real. (Anyone got any plans for, say, 
next Thursday?) 
</P>
<P>
 But until then, there is a group called Victims of Treacherous Lawyers, which 
recently convened its first meeting in Lorraine Fons' living room in Colorado 
Springs. Fons had worried that the crowd might spill over into her dining room. 
</P>
<P>
 Victims of Treacherous Lawyers? I'd have worried the crowd might spill over 
into Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
 As its first order of business, the group asked for names of lawyers in two 
categories: competent and incompetent. Competent got two entries, but one was 
quickly scratched when Dan Wiley said he had personal knowledge that the guy is 
a weasel. 
</P>
<P>
 "They're all weasels," shouted 87-year-old Paul Lanton. 
</P>
<P>
 The feeding frenzy had begun. 
</P>
<P>
 Lanton and others arrived with a feeling for lawyers that can only be compared 
to that deep admiration the guy with the bucket and shovel feels toward the 
parading elephants. 
</P>
<P>
 Occasionally, the anger was broken by humor. Lawyer jokes. But there's no need 
to retell any of them, no need to encourage that type of cheap, juvenile. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Well, OK, perhaps just one: 
</P>
<P>
 Why are a lawyer and a sperm alike? Both have about a one-in-a-million chance 
of becoming a human being.  
</P>
<P>
 Leading the attack was Wiley, a man so infuriated with his lawyer that he 
complained to the Colorado State Bar Assn., which agreed that -- and we're 
paraphrasing here -- he would have been better represented by the Amazing 
Vernon, Circus Llama-Boy. 
</P>
<P>
 But what really makes Wiley's armpit hair braid itself is that the bar told 
him that no record of the admonition of the attorney would be made public. And, 
if Wiley even mentioned it to anyone, he would be in contempt of court; it's 
like, you know, a secret. 
</P>
<P>
 So, say you are about to hire a lawyer. The guy has been disciplined 312 times 
for incompetence and 17 more times for putting thumb tacks on his client's 
courtroom chair. 
</P>
<P>
 You'd like to know the guy's track record before you plunk $10,000 in his lap, 
right? 
</P>
<P>
 Drop dead. The American Bar Assn.'s official explanation for this great 
secrecy? "To maintain the integrity of the legal profession." 
</P>
<P>
 And by golly, hasn't that been a roaring success. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'll tell you about lawyers," barks 72-year-old Betty from somewhere deep in 
Fons' sofa. "They stick together. They take care of each other. You know, like 
gang members." 
</P>
<P>
 Somehow, the victims keep finding the time to tell lawyer jokes. But there's 
no reason to. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 OK, but this is the last time: 
</P>
<P>
 The devil tells a lawyer he'll give him $20 million, fame and a seat on the 
U.S. Supreme Court in exchange for his soul. The lawyer thinks for a minute.  
</P>
<P>
 "Sounds like a good deal," he says. "So what's the catch?"  
</P>
<P>
 The real darn shame in all this is that lawyers try so hard to dispel the 
stereotypes of their profession. 
</P>
<P>
 Take the Huntington Beach lawyer and his son. Seems their law partnership 
broke up a while back, and the proud dad sued his son. 
</P>
<P>
 Earlier this month, in the hallway of Orange County Superior Court, the two 
attorneys spotted each other, took off their coats and started punching the 
bejeebers out of each other. 
</P>
<P>
 Cool. I had a dream about something like that just the other night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
