</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE TIMES 100 / THE BEST PERFORMING COMPANIES IN AMERICA; THE BOTTOM LINE; 
TIMES 100 PERFORMERS SYMBOLIZE A NEW VIGOR; CALIFORNIA'S ECONOMIC STIRRING IS 
EVIDENT IN THE SUCCESS STORIES OF ITS TOP-RANKED COMPANIES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARLA LAZZARESCHI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Although obituaries for the Great California Recession are just now beginning 
to appear, an increasing number of companies in the state were already posting 
healthy and improving returns for their shareholders last year. 
</P>
<P>
 As a whole, The Times 100 -- a ranking of companies that turned in the best 
performances for their shareholders -- rose for the second consecutive year in 
1993 to its highest level since 1988 based on the median performance of firms 
on the list. While this alone is inconclusive proof of the state's improving 
fortunes, some economists note that the results buttress other evidence that 
California's economy is awakening. 
</P>
<P>
 "The man on the street might not feel it yet, because employment is still 
depressed, but we passed the trough of the recession, probably in January," 
said Jack Kyser, chief economist with the Economic Development Corp. of Los 
Angeles County. "I think that by 1995 we'll be able to say, 'We're back.' " 
</P>
<P>
 The Times 100 ranks companies by two-year average return on equity, a ratio 
produced by dividing average common shareholder equity in a company into its 
annual profit. 
</P>
<P>
 Topping the list this year is Inglewood-based Herbalife International Inc., a 
controversial marketing company that for the past several years has enjoyed one 
of the fastest revenue growth rates among publicly held companies in the state. 
</P>
<P>
 The dietary and nutritional supplements company posted an eye-popping 142.2% 
two-year average return on shareholder equity, nearly 2 1/2 times the results 
of the company in the No. 2 spot, Callaway Golf Co. 
</P>
<P>
 The score is also more than twice the 66.6% average return produced by last 
year's No. 1, Total Pharmaceutical Care Inc., a Torrance provider of in-home 
drug treatments that has since been acquired by Abbey Healthcare Group Inc., 
the company in the No. 3 spot on this year's Times 100 list. 
</P>
<P>
 Herbalife sells its products through a network of independent distributors, 
who in turn sell directly to consumers. It is a marketing system that has 
raised regulatory eyebrows in the past. 
</P>
<P>
 Eight years ago, Herbalife, then privately held, was for 18 months the subject 
of state and federal investigations into its direct-marketing arrangements and 
the veracity of claims made for some of its diet products. In October, 1986, 
the company agreed to pay the state $850,000 to settle all outstanding 
allegations, without admitting wrongdoing. State and federal regulators say 
there are no further actions or investigations pending. 
</P>
<P>
 While much of the company's sales growth in recent years has occurred outside 
the United States, last year's growth was attributable in part to strong U.S. 
sales of a new weight-loss product, Thermojetics. The product is based on a 
Chinese herb, ma huang, which contains small amounts of natural ephedrine, an 
alkaloid that constricts blood vessels. 
</P>
<P>
 Diet aids containing that herb are being studied by the U.S. Food and Drug 
Administration. J. Mark Hattendorf, the company's chief financial officer, said 
the review was not aimed specifically at Herbalife, adding, "We feel very 
comfortable the product is safe." 
</P>
<P>
 Although Herbalife's performance dramatically outpaced that of the other 
companies named on the list, the rankings offer ample additional evidence of 
the improving fortunes of California companies. 
</P>
<P>
 For example, the median two-year return on equity in 1993 rose to 22.5% from 
19.4% the previous year. In 1991, it was 17.7%, its lowest level ever.  
</P>
<P>
 In addition, a total of 25 companies had a two-year return on equity of more 
than 30% last year; that compares to 16 companies posting such a figure in 1992 
and 17 firms in 1990, when the state's economy was at a peak, according to data 
compiled by Star Services, a San Francisco business research firm. 
</P>
<P>
 The other companies topping the Times 100 reflect the great emerging business 
opportunities in the nation and underscore the large part these industries play 
in the California economy. Five of the top 10 companies are in health-related 
fields, two are involved in computer software. One makes sporting equipment, 
one is a retailer, and one is a chemical manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
 To be named to the Times 100 list, a company must be based in California and 
have annual sales of more than $50 million. Its stock must have been traded 
publicly since December, 1992, on one of the major exchanges. The company 
cannot be a real estate investment trust or a limited partnership. Its 
long-term, debt-to-equity ratio must be less than 4 to 1, and it must not have 
reported a negative common shareholders' equity for either of the last two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
 Other companies ranked in the top five of The Times 100: 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 2. Callaway Golf Co.: Over the last 10 years, this Carlsbad-based company has 
burst onto the sporting scene with its wildly popular Big Bertha line of metal 
wood golf clubs. These oversized clubs, whose irreverent name was borrowed from 
a German cannon used during World War I, have a large "sweet spot" that makes 
them popular. 
</P>
<P>
 Sales last year were $254.6 million, and profit was $41.2 million. The company 
is named for Ely Callaway, a former textile chieftain who came to the Temecula 
Valley, north of San Diego, in the early 1970s to operate a winery that still 
bears his name. After building a nationally renowned winery in what was a 
small, little-known grape region, Callaway sold the business to Hiram Walker & 
Sons in 1981. A few years later, he invested in a struggling Palm Springs 
manufacturer of golf clubs. 
</P>
<P>
 The company, which first sold shares to the public in early 1992, is making 
its first appearance on The Times 100. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 3. Abbey Healthcare Group Inc.: Thanks to an ambitious decision last year to 
acquire Total Pharmaceutical Care Inc. in Torrance, this Costa Mesa provider of 
at-home care services is making its debut on The Times 100. 
</P>
<P>
 Abbey, which has 200 offices in 45 states, supplies medical equipment and 
respiratory, nutritional and infusion therapies for patients in their homes. It 
is the nation's third-largest home medical supplier, and many industry analysts 
believe it will prosper from efforts by government, employers and insurers to 
reduce medical costs by taking such steps as cutting hospital stays.  
</P>
<P>
 Abbey's roots go back more than 60 years, when it was known as Abbey Rents and 
leased a wide range of equipment. Last year, the company had sales of $380 
million and profit of $14.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 4. Cisco Systems Inc.: The Menlo Park company enjoys a spot in the fast lane 
of the emerging information superhighway. As a supplier of computer networking 
equipment -- its hardware and software link groups of computers -- Cisco has 
benefited from growing demand for products that help companies connect computer 
users within an organization and tie them into the fast-growing Internet data 
network. 
</P>
<P>
 Cisco likes to think of itself as providing the "interchanges" and "on-ramps" 
along the data superhighway, and it recognizes that as traffic increases along 
these networks, demand for its products will rise. "We like to say the more 
bits the better," marketing director Jeff Paine said. 
</P>
<P>
 The company earned $241 million on revenue of $928 million last year. This is 
its second year on The Times 100; it ranked No. 2 last year. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 5. Informix Corp.: The Menlo Park software publisher is making its second 
consecutive appearance on The Times 100. The company, which specializes in 
database software for businesses, enjoyed its best year ever in 1993, earning 
$56.1 million on revenue of nearly $353 million. 
</P>
<P>
 The company's software is used by a variety of businesses, especially the 
hospitality and retail industries. Informix was No. 3 on last year's Times 100. 
</P>
<P>
 The company, which was founded in 1980, provides software that works on every 
type of computer, from mainframe to desktop, through a direct-sales network and 
small computer resellers that tailor the programs to serve individual 
companies. It has about 1,700 employees worldwide. The Times 100 
</P>
